{"type":"message","id":"ff6cead0","parentId":"f4f8078c","timestamp":"2026-04-12T15:08:41.765Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, there's something odd. I see:\n- PID 432: context-api.js\n- PID 597: openclaw-listener\n- PID 599: src/index.js\n\nBut earlier I saw:\n- pid=597: openclaw-listener\n- pid=599: scoring engine (src/index.js)\n- pid=432: context-api.js\n\nAnd the openclaw-gateway is pid=209983. So the processes are:\n- 432: context-api.js (port 3101/3106 health)\n- 597: openclaw-listener (port 3106 health server)\n\n\n- 599: src/index.js = v8 scoring engine (port 3103)\n- 209983: openclaw-gateway (port 3102)\n- 441: python3.8 = scene-classifier (port 3104)\n\nBut 3100 is still a mystery. The listening queue size of 4096 is unusual, and the lack of process information in ss output suggests it might be a kernel-level listener or a process that's exited already.\n\nActually, I'm noticing something odd with the process PPIDs. PID 599 has a PPID of 522, and 597 also shows 522, but 432's parent is PID 1 and 209983's PPID is also 1. That's strange. And then I see 224347 running `for pid in ...` which is my previous exec command. Let me look more carefully at what 522 actually is.","thinkingSignature":"d0f53198e58fd177111f8a6aa2f6e5bdbad136e18d9e774a8889465dc080d080"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_kx295edgyfxj_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ps -ef | grep \"^\\s*522\\s\" | grep -v grep; ls -la /proc/522/exe 2>/dev/null"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_kx295edgyfxj_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /proc/net/tcp | awk 'NR>1 {split($2,a,\":\"); port=strtonum(\"0x\"a[2]); if(port==3100 || port==12228) print}' 2>/dev/null"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_kx295edgyfxj_3","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"printf \"GET / HTTP/1.1\\r\\nHost: 127.0.0.1\\r\\nConnection: close\\r\\n\\r\\n\" | timeout 3 nc 127.0.0.1 3100 2>/dev/null | head -20"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":