{"type":"message","id":"59dc0eb4","parentId":"cf83a061","timestamp":"2026-04-12T15:09:09.985Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Found it! Port 3100 is in /proc/net/tcp6 (IPv6 table), and the inode is 24308. But I can't find which process has this inode. Let me check the sockets.\n\nActually, there's something very odd - the inode is 24308 but there's no process using it according to ss. The inode might be held by a process that's now zombie or the socket is orphaned.\n\nLet me look at what socket inode 24308 is connected to. Actually, the issue is that this socket has become orphaned - the process that created it has exited but the kernel still holds the port. This is a known Linux behavior.\n \nSo the 3100 port is in a orphaned state - no process owns it anymore. This is likely a leftover from a crashed or killed Node.js process. The port is essentially zombie at this point and should be cleaned up by the kernel, though there might be a way to forcefully remove it.\n\nI still need to check what's running on 3105.","thinkingSignature":"abccfb66ff631ab30a72ad077d0a9f243c521663b21e28b718527457a8965e95"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_l7zcnsw8l4lj_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /proc/net/tcp6 | awk '{print $2, $10}' | grep -i \"c25\" # 3105 = 0xC29"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_l7zcnsw8l4lj_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# 3105 = 0xC29\nprintf \"3105 decimal = 0xC29\\n\"\ncat /proc/net/tcp6 | head -1\ncat /proc/net/tcp6 | grep \"C29\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":70604,"output":331,"cacheRead":15172,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":86107,"cost":{"input":0.0211812,"output":0.0003972,"cacheRead":0.0009103199999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.02248872}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776006537450,"responseId":"062ae88a9fe8c6f15b82c7ecf032fe41"}}
