{"type":"message","id":"bca55bb1","parentId":"3fc4b563","timestamp":"2026-04-12T17:39:46.182Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The handler is a JavaScript file that imports from OpenClaw's internal modules. This means the hook has access to OpenClaw's internal APIs. The handler exports a default function that receives an `event` object.\n\nMy handler.ts uses `node:http` and `node:fs` which are standard Node.js APIs available to hooks. However, the hook might be compiled/transpiled before execution.\n\nLooking at the session-memory hook, it uses `createSubsystemLogger`, `resolveStateDir`, etc. from OpenClaw internals. These are pre-built hooks.\n\nFor a managed hook (installed in `~/.openclaw/hooks/`), OpenClaw should compile TypeScript or load JavaScript directly. \n\nI should convert my handler to plain JavaScript to avoid any transpilation complications. I'll write it without TypeScript imports—just standard Node.js APIs and basic type checks in comments.","thinkingSignature":"e97ce4e4ddd1867ca2ac87dfbfcdaa3956a42254c335b9fade358756d5070cd4"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ijokr5dxam2d_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/home/ai/.openclaw/hooks/auto-score-classify/handler.js","content":"// auto-score-classify hook\n// Concurrent classification (3104) + scoring (3103) on every inbound message\n\nimport fs from \"node:fs\";\nimport path from \"node:path\";\nimport http from \"node:http\";\n\nasync function fetchJSON(url, body, timeoutMs = 3000) {\n  return new Promise((resolve) => {\n    const postData = JSON.stringify(body);\n    const req = http.request(\n      url,\n      {\n        method: \"POST\",\n        headers: { \"Content-Type\": \"application/json\", \"Content-Length\": Buffer.byteLength(postData) },\n      },\n      (res) => {\n        let data = \"\";\n        res.on(\"data\", (chunk) => (data += chunk));\n        res.on(\"end\", () => {\n          try { resolve(JSON.parse(data)); }\n          catch {