{"type":"message","id":"caeabd28","parentId":"dea2f0ae","timestamp":"2026-04-12T18:16:21.363Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to do single-point thinking on Session Summary specifically. Let me think deeply about just this one component.\n\nSession Summary - what does it really need to do?\n\nThe goal: when a session ends (or periodically), generate a summary that captures the key decisions, outcomes, and context, write it to memory/, and read it at bootstrap.\n\nLet me think about the specific requirements, challenges, and approaches for just this one thing.\n\n**What is a \"session\"?**\n- In OpenClaw, a session is a continuous conversation. It can end via `/new`, `/reset`, or timeout.\n\n\n- Within a session, there might be multiple \"turns\" or \"tasks\" - each user request might be a distinct unit.\n\n**When to generate summary?**\n- Option A: On every user message (too expensive, too noisy)\n- Option B: On session end (/new, /reset, timeout) - makes sense\n- Option C: On idle (no activity for X minutes) - could supplement B\n- Option D: On every N messages - periodic checkpoint\n\nThe session-memory hook already captures raw conversation on /new and /reset, but that's not quite the same as a summary with key decisions and context.\n\n**What should a summary contain?**\nI'm thinking through the core components: what the user was trying to accomplish, what decisions were made, what came out of it, any important info discovered, what still needs follow-up, and any patterns worth noting. This isn't a transcript—it's more like meeting notes.\n\n**The challenge is that generating a good summary requires calling the LLM**, which costs money and takes time, so I need to figure out when to do it and how to do it efficiently. The summary has to be written to disk and read at bootstrap, but there's a bootstrapping problem—the LLM has to generate its own summary, which means the summary generation itself needs to be lightweight and reliable.\n\n**There are two ways to trigger it**: either hook into the session end events (/new, /reset, timeout) and generate the summary then, or use a heartbeat that runs periodically and generates a summary of recent messages. The event-driven approach is cleaner, but I need to verify the hook actually fires before session end so I can capture the conversation state.\n\n**The session-memory hook already does something similar**—it extracts the last 15 messages, generates a slug, and writes to memory. The problem is it saves raw content rather than a summary, so I could either modify that hook to generate a summary instead, or create a new hook that runs on session end events, generates the summary via LLM, and writes it to memory.\n\n**I'm also realizing there's a timing issue**: when /new or /reset fires, the session state is still accessible, but I need to figure out if the hook runs before or after the session clears, and whether I can pass the previous session's content to the LLM for summarization.\n\n**The key is deciding what actually needs to happen**: I need to hook into session end events (command:new or command:reset), extract the conversation history, generate a summary through the LLM rather than storing raw messages, write that summary to memory with a descriptive filename, and make sure bootstrap reads it back on startup.\n\n**The bootstrap reading part is already handled** through the session-memory hook, so I just need to make sure the summary is in the right place. Now I need to figure out how to actually generate the summary using the available LLM endpoints.\n\nI can call the same LLM the user uses, but that requires an LLM API key and adds cost and latency. Alternatively, there's a slug generator in the existing session-memory hook that uses the LLM to create a filename, so I could follow a similar pattern for the summary itself. The most practical approach would be to create a new hook that listens for session:end events, reads the session content, and sends it to the LLM for summarization.\n\nFor the hook, I'd hook into the session:end event rather than relying on the flaky session:compact:before event. The key constraint is that this needs to run after the conversation ends but before the session clears, so I can capture the full context. Looking at the OpenClaw hooks documentation, I don't see a built-in session:end event, but command:new and command:reset both indicate when a session is ending. The session-memory hook already handles extracting content on these events, so I'd need to either modify that hook or create a parallel one that generates the summary instead of just storing raw content.\n\nThe challenge is timing—if I generate a summary using the LLM during the hook, it adds latency to /new and /reset commands, which could make them feel slow. I could run it asynchronously after the command returns, or use a simpler approach like a rule-based summary that captures key elements without needing LLM processing.\n\nLooking at what's already built in the system, there's a v8 Router on 3102 that I could leverage to call the LLM, and the context API on 3106 handles message storage. Rather than spinning up a separate summarization service, I should explore using the existing hook infrastructure to trigger summary generation when a session ends.","thinkingSignature":"0010875edb8b97e639f217a4f33555d2edafc22ce10f030d2b6ca940d221c2c1"},{"type":"text","text":"逐个深度思考 Session 摘要这个单点。\n\n---\n\n**Session 摘要的本质问题**\n\n```\nsession 结束时 → 提取什么 → 怎么提炼 → 写到哪里 → 怎么被读\n```\n\n---\n\n**第一个决策点：什么时候触发**\n\nOpenClaw 的 session 结束信号只有：\n- `command:new` — 用户发 /new\n- `command:reset` — 用户发 /reset\n- 超时（没有明确事件）\n\n`session:compact:before` 不适合——那是压缩前，不是 session 结束。\n\n**触发点应该是 `command:new` / `command:reset`**。现有 `session-memory` hook 已经在用这两个事件。\n\n---\n\n**第二个决策点：用什么生成摘要**\n\n| 方案 | 优点 | 缺点 |\n|------|------|------|\n| LLM 生成 | 质量高，能提炼决策 | 延迟、API 成本、可能失败 |\n| 规则模板 | 快速稳定 | 质量低，无推理 |\n| 混合 | 规则兜底 + LLM 增强 | 实现复杂 |\n\n**现实路径**：LLM 生成为主，失败时用规则模板降级。\n\n---\n\n**第三个决策点：LL从哪来**\n\n现有基础设施：\n- 3102 (v8 Router) — 反向代理，可以转发 LLM 请求\n- 3106 (Context API) — 存了 session 历史\n\n**最直接**：hook 里直接调 3102 的 LLM 接口，session-memory hook 已经在做类似的事（`generateSlugViaLLM`）。\n\n---\n\n**第四个决策点：摘要写到哪里**\n\n```\nmemory/YYYY-MM-DD-{slug}.md\n```\n\n文件名：日期 + slug（LLM 生成或规则）\n内容格式：\n\n```markdown\n# Session Summary: 2026-04-13\n\n## 主题\n用户讨论了...\n\n## 关键决策\n- 决策1：...\n- 决策2：...\n\n## 重要发现\n- ...\n\n## 待跟进\n- ...\n\n## 相关实体\n（自动关联到 LLM Wiki entities/ 的链接）\n```\n\n---\n\n**第五个决策点：bootstrap 怎么读**\n\nAGENTS.md 第4步已经有了：\n\n```\nRead session context: look for ~/.openclaw/sessions/main@*/context.json\n```\n\ncontext.json 里放的是分类/评分，不是摘要。\n\n**需要扩展**：session 结束时生成的摘要文件路径，也注入到 bootstrap 上下文，或者修改 AGENTS.md 让它同时读 `memory/YYYY-MM-DD-{latest}.md`。\n\n---\n\n**第六个决策点：延迟问题**\n\n/new 和 /reset 是同步命令，用户在等返回。\n\n如果 hook 里调 LLM 生成摘要，会阻塞返回。\n\n**解决**：hook 触发后，摘要生成异步执行，不阻塞 /new /reset 的返回。摘要写完后下次 bootstrap 自然能读到。\n\n---\n\n**实施步骤（单点思考结论）**\n\n```\n1. 写一个新 hook（或扩展 session-memory）\n   - 监听 command:new / command:reset\n   - 读取 session 历史（session-memory hook 已有的逻辑）\n   - 调 LLM 生成摘要\n   - 写入 memory/YYYY-MM-DD-{slug}.md\n\n2. 修改 AGENTS.md bootstrap\n   - 读最新摘要文件（不只是 context.json）\n\n3. 异步执行\n   - hook 触发后立即返回\n   - 摘要生成在后台\n```\n\n---\n\n**唯一的前提**：hook 里调 LLM 的方式要稳定。当前 session-memory 用的是 `generateSlugViaLLM`，可以复用同样的 LLM 调用逻辑。\n\n---\n\n同意这个方向吗？"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":1801,"cacheRead":94547,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":96348,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0.0021612,"cacheRead":0.005672819999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.007834019999999999}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1776017732945,"responseId":"062b14442eb630a4e22efef828239870"}}
