{"type":"message","id":"8d7c506f","parentId":"414d3556","timestamp":"2026-04-12T18:20:16.892Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! There are multiple hooks in ~/.openclaw/hooks/:\n- `context-hook.js`\n- `on-command-error.sh`\n- `on-message.sh`\n- `self-improvement.js`\n- `auto-score-classify/` (a directory with HOOK.md + handler.js)\n- `session-summary/` (appears after my listing - wait, this was created in step 1, but it seems it exists... wait, the first `ls` showed the directory listing already, so it seems session-summary directory already exists? Let me re-read. The first `ls` showed: HOOK.md, auto-score-classify, context-hook.js, handler.js, handler.ts, on-command-error.sh, on-message.sh, self-improvement.js. The second `ls` for `auto-score-classify/` showed HOOK.md and handler.js.\n\n\nSo `session-summary` doesn't appear in the first `ls`, meaning it's not yet created. All the existing hooks are `.js`, `.sh` files directly in the hooks directory, not organized into subdirectories. Only `auto-score-classify` follows the subdirectory pattern with its own HOOK.md and handler.js. The other hooks like context-hook.js, on-command-error.sh, on-message.sh, and self-improvement.js are sitting directly in the hooks folder as individual files.\n\nThis means I need to decide whether to put session-summary in its own subdirectory like auto-score-classify, or as a standalone file like the others. Since I'm writing TypeScript, I'd need to compile it to JavaScript first before placing it in the hooks directory. Let me check the self-improvement.js file to understand what the compiled output should look like.","thinkingSignature":"91fe629053af3d6e42968d66b61abc0448ef8ddf2a485212b7aa5a611b606695"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_4vth9ff5hfrp_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"head -20 ~/.openclaw/hooks/self-improvement.js 2>/dev/null","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2