{"type":"message","id":"11c5ff4b","parentId":"253843bd","timestamp":"2026-04-12T18:20:53.215Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, npx is available. Let me think about whether to use TypeScript or plain ESM JavaScript.\n\nFor code quality being high, TypeScript is better. But the compilation step adds complexity. \n\nLet me think about a middle path: write the handler in clean ESM JavaScript (which TypeScript would compile to), with JSDoc type annotations for documentation. This way it's immediately runnable without a compilation step, but the types are documented.\n\nActually, the user said \"代码质量要高\" - let me think about this more carefully.\n\nOption A: TypeScript → compile → handler.js\n- Pros: Type safety, better IDE support\n- Cons: Compilation step, more complex deployment\n\n\n- Pros: No compilation, immediately runnable, still high quality with JSDoc\n- Cons: No compile-time type checking\n\nI'm leaning toward Option B for a hook that needs to be deployed quickly and debugged in production—clean ESM JavaScript with JSDoc gives us clarity without the compilation overhead. Though TypeScript would technically be cleaner for code quality, the practical advantage of skipping the build step is significant.\n\nNow I need to work through the session-summary hook step by step. First, I should verify whether to use a directory structure or single file, then create the implementation. The directory approach seems better since it matches the existing auto-score-classify pattern, though looking at the actual files in ~/.openclaw/hooks/, I see most are single .js files rather than directories. Let me go with the directory structure for consistency with that pattern.\n\nActually, the existing hooks are a mix of .js and .sh files in the root, while only auto-score-classify uses the directory pattern. I'll follow that directory pattern for session-summary since it groups the hook and documentation together.\n\nFor the implementation, I'm deciding between writing it in TypeScript for better type safety or using plain ESM JavaScript. TypeScript would give us compile-time checking, but it requires a compilation step that could complicate deployment and take time to set up. Given the user's emphasis on code quality and wanting to move quickly, I think starting with TypeScript makes sense, though I should be mindful that the extra compilation step might slow us down initially.\n\nI'm settling on writing the handler in plain ESM JavaScript instead—it's immediately runnable without a build step, and I can add JSDoc annotations to document types clearly. This gives us maintainability without the overhead of TypeScript compilation. Before I start though, I should check the existing openclaw-classifier service to see what patterns are already established.","thinkingSignature":"f48ffc1b55e66cf1610534f450d3705932c0af8fe92f6f4e72be7dbef070ae16"},{"type":"text","text":"**Step 2 结论**：ESM 可用（Node.js 原生），直接写 `.js` 不需要编译。\n\n---\n\n**Step 3：确认 session-memory hook 的事件处理逻辑**\n\n`session-memory` hook 是官方示例，它的 `handler.js` 读取 session 文件的逻辑是参考模板：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ogjq4awvzyex_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"getRecentSession\\|sessionFile\\|sessionKey\" ~/.nvm/versions/node/v22.22.1/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/bundled/session-memory/handler.js 2>/dev/null | head -15","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":82206,"output":673,"cacheRead":17776,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":100655,"cost":{"input":0.024661799999999998,"output":0.0008076,"cacheRead":0.0010665599999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.026535959999999997}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776018034513,"responseId":"062b1571622cca70199068b14a54e66d"}}
{"type":"message","id":"885c1686","parentId":"11c5ff4b","timestamp":"2026-04-12T18:20:53.304Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_ogjq4awvzyex_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"22:async function getRecentSessionContent(sessionFilePath, messageCount = 15) {\n24:\t\tconst lines = (await fs.readFile(sessionFilePath, \"utf-8\")).trim().split(\"\\n\");\n43:async function getRecentSessionContentWithResetFallback(sessionFilePath, messageCount = 15) {\n44:\tconst primary = await getRecentSessionContent(sessionFilePath, messageCount);\n47:\t\tconst dir = path.dirname(sessionFilePath);\n48:\t\tconst resetPrefix = `${path.basename(sessionFilePath)}.reset.`;\n51:\t\treturn await getRecentSessionContent(path.join(dir, resetCandidates[resetCandidates.length - 1]), messageCount) || primary;\n88:\tif (!params.cfg || !params.workspaceDir) return params.sessionKey;\n90:\tconst parsed = parseAgentSessionKey(params.sessionKey);\n91:\tif (!workspaceAgentId || !parsed || workspaceAgentId === parsed.agentId) return params.sessionKey;\n108:\t\tconst agentId = resolveAgentIdFromSessionKey(event.sessionKey);\n113:\t\t\tsessionKey: event.sessionKey\n121:\t\tlet currentSessionFile = sessionEntry.sessionFile || void 0;\n140:\t\t\tsessionFile: currentSessionFile,\n143:\t\tconst sessionFile = currentSessionFile || void 0;"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":48,"aggregated":"22:async function getRecentSessionContent(sessionFilePath, messageCount = 15) {\n24:\t\tconst lines = (await fs.readFile(sessionFilePath, \"utf-8\")).trim().split(\"\\n\");\n43:async function getRecentSessionContentWithResetFallback(sessionFilePath, messageCount = 15) {\n44:\tconst primary = await getRecentSessionContent(sessionFilePath, messageCount);\n47:\t\tconst dir = path.dirname(sessionFilePath);\n48:\t\tconst resetPrefix = `${path.basename(sessionFilePath)}.reset.`;\n51:\t\treturn await getRecentSessionContent(path.join(dir, resetCandidates[resetCandi