{"type":"message","id":"04c9a4cb","parentId":"69b444b7","timestamp":"2026-04-12T18:22:33.217Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"No session history .jsonl files anywhere. This confirms that the gateway stores session data in memory (not as .jsonl files), and only writes to disk when the session-memory hook is triggered on /new or /reset.\n\nSo the session content IS available to the session-memory hook, but only at the moment of /new or /reset, because the gateway passes it to the hook at that point.\n\nLet me look at this from the perspective of the session-memory hook's actual behavior. When /new is triggered:\n1. The gateway calls the session-memory hook with the session content2. The hook writes it to a file in memory/\n3. The hook also generates a slug via LLM\n\nFor my session-summary hook, I could piggyback on this - but I need the content at the time of /new/reset.\n\n\nThe core constraint is that I can only access session content during the /new or /reset event when the gateway provides it, so I need to generate the summary at that same moment rather than trying to read from a file afterward. The gateway passes the session content directly to the hook in memory, so at that point I have everything I need—I just need to generate the summary and write it out as part of the same hook execution. it could use `context.previousSessionEntry` which contains the session that just ended (before /new was pressed).\n\nWait, let me re-read: `context.previousSessionEntry || context.sessionEntry`. So `previousSessionEntry` is the ended session, and `sessionEntry` is the current session. On `/new`, `previousSessionEntry` would be the session that just ended.\n\nActually, I think I'm overthinking this. Let me look at the actual handler event structure. On `command:new`:\n- `context.previousSessionEntry` = the session that just ended (has sessionFile, sessionId, etc.)\n- `context.sessionEntry` = the NEW session that was just created\n\nSo `previousSessionEntry.sessionFile` points to the file of the session that ended, which is exactly what I need.\n\nFor my session-summary hook, I should use `context.previousSessionEntry?.sessionFile` as the primary source, falling back to `context.sessionEntry?.sessionFile` if needed. I also need to account for the fact that session files might be small or empty if the session was short, and I should handle `.reset.` files as a fallback.\n\nLet me stop analyzing and just build it with these practical constraints in place.","thinkingSignature":"57bbe60f6fc7c4529e4a23d0a7b56f0394d1eb8db9898a8d02fc88003e2f483a"},{"type":"text","text":"**Step 3 关键发现**：session 历史文件 (`.jsonl`) 不存在于 `~/.openclaw/sessions/`，session 内容由 gateway 在 hook 事件中传递。\n\nSession-memory hook 的做法：\n- `context.previousSessionEntry.sessionFile` — 刚结束的 session 文件\n- `context.sessionEntry.sessionFile` — 当前新 session 文件\n\n---\n\n**Step 4：确定 session-summary hook 的读取策略**\n\n```\n触发 (/new 或 /reset)\n    ↓\n读 context.previousSessionEntry.sessionFile  ← 这是刚结束的那个 session\n    ↓\n文件不存在 → 读 .reset. 备份文件\n    ↓\n文件存在 → 读内容，调 LLM 生成摘要\n    ↓\n写 memory/YYYY-MM-DD-{slug}.md\n```\n\n---\n\n**Step 5：现在创建 HOOK.md**\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_u337ynyjjca3_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -p ~/.openclaw/hooks/session-summary && echo \"dir created\"","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":87413,"output":730,"cacheRead":17776,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":105919,"cost":{"input":0.026223899999999998,"output":0.0008759999999999999,"cacheRead":0.0010665599999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.028166459999999997}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776018135806,"responseId":"062b15d7327f8544bb6909e9104ca7a0"}}
