{"type":"message","id":"26ab4392","parentId":"dc8f49ec","timestamp":"2026-04-12T18:35:58.545Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The hook listens for `message:preprocessed`. The question is: does OpenClaw's message pipeline actually emit `message:preprocessed` events? And is the bootstrap process reading context.json at the right time?\n\nLet me also check if the context.json is being read by the agent during bootstrap. The AGENTS.md says to read it, but is there actually a mechanism that does this, or does the agent just read the file on startup?\n\nI should also look at the openclaw docs to understand when message:preprocessed fires and whether the agent has access to the context.json during its bootstrap.\n\nActually, there's a fundamental issue here: the hook writes context.json to the session directory, but the agent (when it starts a new session) may not have access to previous session's context.json. \n\nSo the real problem is that context.json gets written to the previous session's directory, but when a new session starts, the agent is bootstrapped fresh without any knowledge of what was written before. I'm realizing there's a fundamental mismatch between what the documentation claims and what's actually happening. The `message:preprocessed` hook fires for every inbound message before the agent receives it, which means when a user sends \"检查一下\", the hook runs first and writes classification data to context.json before the agent bootstr and processes that same message. But the agent's bootstrap only happens once at the start of a session, not for each individual message, so these are happening at different times. The hook would fire for the *next* message, not the current one. So the context.json wouldn't have the current message's classification.\n\nActually wait - let me re-read the hook event flow. The `message:preprocessed` event says \"After all media and link understanding completes\". This fires for EVERY inbound message. So when a user sends a message:\n\n1. Message received\n2. Media/link processing\n3. `message:preprocessed` event fires → hook writes to context.json\n4. Agent receives message\n\nSo the context.json would have the *previous* message's data by the time the agent processes the current one. That's actually fine for a \"last message analysis\" use case, but not for \"current message analysis\".\n\nNow I need to check whether the bootstrap phase actually reads context.json, or if that's just described in AGENTS.md but not actually implemented anywhere.","thinkingSignature":"b23065e8cea8cc02db2d04471ac2ce25463e3411ab7b52b2d5ccb89db80ea4fc"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_uyq39no1m4d8_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"find ~/.nvm/versions/node/v22.22.1/lib/node_modules/openclaw -name \"*.js\" 2>/dev/null | xargs grep -l \"context.json\\|session.*context\\|bootstrap.*session\" 2>/dev/null | grep -v node_modules | head -5","timeout":5}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_uyq39no1m4d8_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"find ~/.openclaw/hooks -name \"*.js\" | xargs grep -l \"bootstrap\\|session.*start\" 2>/dev/null | head -5","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":102362,"output":636,"cacheRead":17846,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":120844,"cost":{"input":0.0307086,"output":0.0007632,"cacheRead":0.0010707599999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.03254256}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776018942255,"responseId":"062b18fe7e7a08fade4647711efd0177"}}
