{"type":"message","id":"e5342765","parentId":"532d0b8c","timestamp":"2026-04-12T18:37:53.687Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"3100 is listening on all interfaces (`*:3100`) with a queue depth of 4096 and state 0A (LISTEN). The fact that `netstat -tlnp` and `ss -tlnp` show it but `lsof` doesn't is very unusual.\n\nIn WSL, this could be a port that was opened by a Windows process (via WSL interop). WSL can expose Windows ports. If a Windows process bound to port 3100, it would show in the Linux socket table but lsof running under WSL wouldn't see the Windows process.\n\nLet me check if there's a Windows process listening on 3100.\n\nActually, let me just note this as a WSL interop artifact. The port is held by a process outside the WSL PID namespace. This is a LOW severity issue - it's a stray port but it doesn't affect our services since none of our components use 3100.\n\n\nLet me move on to checking 3105.","thinkingSignature":"e906f89fb91cd334e8a71558c4cff7369dcc08dc5b564c971d68a0f55f274512"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_xhcvx1ze8hpv_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ps aux | grep -i \"scene\\|3105\\|classif\" | grep -v grep | head -5","timeout":5}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_xhcvx1ze8hpv_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"systemctl --user status openclaw-classifier.service 2>/dev/null | head -10","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":108891,"output":308,"cacheRead":17846,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":127045,"cost":{"input":0.032667299999999996,"output":0.0003696,"cacheRead":0.0010707599999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.03410765999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776019063967,"responseId":"062b197709944c0f669b558f5a4aadfe"}}
