{"type":"message","id":"1ef22fe9","parentId":"007ec4c5","timestamp":"2026-04-12T18:49:29.162Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Current session file is at `/home/ai/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/2d625705-5c75-484e-bcf0-29f5034c6b20.jsonl` and it was modified recently (it's the current session).\n\nWhen I send `/new`, the gateway will:1. Create a new session file\n2. Fire the `command:new` hook\n3. The hook should read from `previousSessionEntry.sessionFile` which should be this current session file\n\nBut I still don't know the exact sessionFile path that will be in the event context.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The session key for the current session is `agent:main:main`. The gateway must know the session file path for this. \n\nIf I can figure out what session file the gateway is actively writing to, I could potentially send a test message that simulates what happens during a reset. The current session file at `/home/ai/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/2d625705-5c75-484e-bcf0-29f5034c6b20.jsonl` was modified recently and contains our entire conversation, so that's likely where the gateway is writing right now.\n\nIf I trigger `/new`, the hook would receive the previous session file path from the gateway, read its content, and generate a summary before creating a fresh session file. The problem is I can't easily trigger `/new` in this webchat environment without disrupting things. Maybe I should just do it and observe what happens.\n\nActually, wait—the user explicitly asked me to test step by step. If I just send `/new` right now, I'll lose this conversation and won't be able to report back what I found. That's counterproductive. I should ask them to trigger `/new` from their end so they can verify whether the summary file appears in the memory directory afterward.","thinkingSignature":"f8da97e140f9b35d4fd57a97c0262cfac701d0ed500fd7a62050235e3d8a577d"},{"type":"text","text":"我发现一个问题——通过消息发 `/new` 会重置当前 session，我没办法